message.content:
In the given grammar every derivation from the start symbol S must begin with one of the two rules

1. S → NT3 NT4  
2. S → NT8 NT2  

Consider what the last token of the derived string can be in each case.

Case 1: S → NT3 NT4  
The rightmost part of the string is produced entirely by NT4.  
NT4 has only the following possibilities:

NT4 → NT2 NT1 , NT4 → 't6' , NT4 → 't8' , NT4 → 't1'

Thus the final token generated by NT4 must be

• t6  (if NT4 → 't6')  
• t8  (if NT4 → 't8')  
• t1  (if NT4 → 't1')  
• t8 , t3 or t5 (if NT4 → NT2 NT1, because NT1 can only be 't8', 't3', or 't5')

So with rule 1 the whole string must end in t1, t3, t5, t6 or t8.

Case 2: S → NT8 NT2  
The first symbol NT8 is a single terminal ('t8' or 't3'), so the very first
token of the string would have to be t8 or t3.

Now look at the string we have to test:

… t2  (its last token)  
t5 …  (its first token)

• The last token is t2, which is impossible for rule 1.  
• The first token is t5, which is impossible for rule 2.

Hence the string cannot be produced by either of the only two possible
derivations from S, so it is not in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S has only two possible productions:  

1. S → NT3 NT4  
2. S → NT8 NT2  

So the very first token of any derived string must come either from NT3 (alternative 1) or from NT8 (alternative 2).

• NT8 can derive only the single terminals ‘t8’ or ‘t3’.  
  → With rule 2 the first token could be ‘t8’ or ‘t3’, never ‘t2’.

• NT3 can be

   – a single terminal ‘t0’, ‘t5’ or ‘t7’ (not ‘t2’), or  
   – NT3 → NT7 NT5, so the first token would come from NT7.

  NT7, in turn, can be  
   – one of the single terminals ‘t6’, ‘t0’, ‘t5’, ‘t7’, ‘t8’, ‘t3’ (not ‘t2’),  
   – NT7 → NT8 NT4 (first token then ‘t8’ or ‘t3’), or  
   – NT7 → NT4 NT6 (first token from NT4).

  NT4 can be  
   – a single terminal ‘t6’, ‘t8’, or ‘t1’ (not ‘t2’), or  
   – NT4 → NT2 NT1, putting the first token in NT2.

  NT2’s single-terminal options are ‘t7’, ‘t2’, ‘t3’, ‘t4’; it could indeed produce ‘t2’.  
  But if NT4 uses NT2 NT1, the second token must come from NT1, whose
  terminals are only ‘t8’, ‘t3’, or ‘t5’.  Therefore the pair produced by NT4 in that
  case must be ‘t2 t8’, ‘t2 t3’, or ‘t2 t5’—never ‘t2 t1’.

Hence, no derivation starting from S can produce a string whose very first token is ‘t2’.  
The given string begins with ‘t2’, so it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

In Chomsky normal form every interior production is binary and the order of the two sub-phrases is fixed.

S has only two possibilities:

1. S → NT3 NT4     (prefix generated by NT3, suffix by NT4)  
2. S → NT8 NT2     (prefix generated by NT8, suffix by NT2)

Look at the last token of the given string, which is ‘t0’.

Case 1:  If S → NT3 NT4, the last token must be generated by NT4.
          NT4 can produce
          • a single terminal  (t6, t8, t1) or
          • NT4 → NT2 NT1, where the last token comes from NT1.
          NT1 can produce only t8, t3 or t5.
          Hence NT4 can never produce a final token t0.  
          So the string cannot be derived through S → NT3 NT4.

Case 2:  If S → NT8 NT2, the first token must be generated by NT8.
          NT8 can produce only t8 or t3.
          The given string starts with t4, so this derivation is impossible.

Since both rules for S are impossible for the given string, the grammar cannot generate the string.

No
